Good to hear from you, jt miller.  I had forgotten the name &quot;winter soldier investigation.&quot;  <br>
We had one of those in Seattle in the winter of 1970, at which an active duty GI who was AWOL testified.  It was a great event planned by GIs and civilians, and I think those sorts of things scared the shit out of the top brass, and made them more eager to end the war before their whole army disintegrated.  What was &quot;Dewey Canyon III?&quot;  In any case, I never met any braver people than the GIs who worked on the Shelter Half in Tacoma, Washington, and the airmen and WAFs who ran a coffeehouse (&quot;Off the Runway&quot;) in Holyoke, Mass, and published a newspaper called the 99th Bummer.  the Air Force's reaction was to give them all discharges, but we still managed to get our messages of support of the GIs on to the base.  The friendships I made then with folks in the military have lasted for 25 years.  I second your question &quot;what marine who was killed by a protester?&quot;  The history my kids study in school is full of such erroneous stereotypes, and if I want them to learn about what it was really like, I have to teach them myself.  For example, who remembers when Lyndon Johnson sent troops from the 101st airborne brigade to Chicago to help quell the anti-war demonstrators, and many of the troops refused to go?  They raised a simple question: &quot;Why do harm to our friends who are trying to stop the war?&quot;  
